06707nam a22009015i 9780691197678DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20191992nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911976787 a10.1515/97806911976782doi  a(DE-B1597)527620  a(OCoLC)1096185422  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPA4037b.H775 2019 7aLIT0041902bisacsh04a883/.0122200aHomer's Ancient Readers :bThe Hermeneutics of Greek Epic's Earliest Exegetes /ced. by Robert Lamberton, John J. Keaney. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1992  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Legacy Library ;v540200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tAbbreviations -- tCHAPTER ONE. Bard and Audience in Homer -- tCHAPTER TWO. Aristotle's Reading of Homer and Its Background -- tCHAPTER THREE. Stoic Readings of Homer -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Hermeneutic Lines and Circles: Aristarchus and Crates on the Exegesis of Homer -- tCHAPTER FIVE. The Neoplatonists and the Spiritualization of Homer -- tCHAPTER SIX. The Byzantines and Homer -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. Renaissance Readers of Homer's Ancient Readers -- tContributors -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough the influence of Homer on Western literature has long commanded critical attention, little has been written on how various generations of readers have found menaing in his texts. These seven essays explore the ways in which the Illiad and the Odyssey have been read from the time of Homer through the Renaissance. By asking what questions early readers expected the texts to answer and looking at how these expectations changed over time, the authors clarify the position of the Illiad and the Odyssey in the intellectual world of antiqueity while offering historical insight into the nature of reading.The collection surveys the entire field of preserved ancient interpretations of Homer, beginning with the fictional audiences portrayed within the poems themselves, proceedings to readings by Aristotle, the Stoics, and Aristarchus and Crates, and culminating in the spritiualized allegorical reading current among Platonists of the fifth and sixth centuries C.E. The influence of these ancient interpretations is then examined in Byzantium and in the Latin West during the Renaissance. Contributors to this volume are Robert Browning, Anthony Grafton, Robert Lamberton, A.A. Long, James Porter, Nicholas Richardson, and Charles Segal.Robert Lamberton is Assistant Professor of Classics and John J. Keaney is Professor of Classics, both at Princeton University.Originally published in 1992.The Princeton Legacy Library uses the latest print-on-demand technology to again make available previously out-of-print books from the distinguished backlist of Princeton University Press. These editions preserve the original texts of these important books while presenting them in durable paperback and hardcover editions. The goal of the Princeton Legacy Library is to vastly increase access to the rich scholarly heritage found in the thousands of books published by Princeton University Press since its founding in 1905.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAuthors and readerszGreecexHistoryvCongresses. 0aEpic poetry, GreekxHistory and criticismxTheory, etcvCongresses. 0aEpic poetry, GreekxHistory and criticismxTheory, etc.vCongresses. 0aMythology, Greek, in literaturevCongresses. 0aReader-response criticismvCongresses. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh1 aBrowning, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrafton, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1